                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d1026">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">File No. 763.72/2969</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Ambassador in Great Britain</hi> (<persName
                        corresp="#p_PWH1" type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Page</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <seg rendition="#center">[Telegram]</seg>
                </opener>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">London</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1916-10-23T18:00:00+00:00">
                            <hi rend="italic">October 23, 1916, 6 p. m.</hi>
                        </date>
                        <lb/> [<hi rend="italic">Received 6.30 p. m.</hi>]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>5070. Your 3968, October 22, 5 p. m. The British Government have made no request
                    of me, but both Government and public are anxious to know precisely what
                    happened and there is no authoritative way to obtain information except by our
                    Government’s making facts known. In cases mentioned by you there would be no
                    objection if no loss of ships nor were lives put in jeopardy [<hi rend="italic"
                        >sic</hi>]. Since British ships were sunk and British subjects put into
                    small boats, there is a natural curiosity to know precisely what happened and
                    consequent criticism of our Government for not making facts known which can be
                    made known in no other way.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <persName corresp="#p_PWH1">
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Page</hi>
                        </persName>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
    </text>
